EIS and CV are commonly techniques used to verify the interfacial impedance, electrical conductivity and stability of electrodes (Fig. 5
                        ). EIS curve of NF/Au NPs/N-CPDs@FLBP/SPE displays the smallest semicircle in the high-frequency region and almost a straight line in the low-frequency region, which demonstrates the lowest Rct
                         and fastest charge-transfer (Fig. 5a). CV curves are displayed to estimate the electrical conductivity of different modified electrodes. As shown the curves in Fig. 5b and the values in Table S2, the reduction peak currents on NF/FLBP/SPE were higher than that of NF/N-CPDs/SPE, and NF/Au NPs/SPE, indicating FLBP contributed the crucial promoting effect on the electron transfer. Besides, the highest redox peak current appeared on NF/Au NPs/N-CPDs@FLBP/SPE proves the synergistic effects of the conductive AuNPs, N-CPDs and FLBP.
